# ReadyPlay Recovery — heredoc-button cassette for the ecosystem

## The verbatim source (stated by Avery 2026-05-23)

> mark the solution and make sure it is in the quick recovery for the nephew system to recovery the readyplay ecosystem - heredoc button exectition too and all - the whole 9.

Said after the 2026-05-23 outage where `readyplay.app` returned HTTP 502 for ~hours because `readyplay-marketing` pm2 had a stuck `cwd` (`/opt/readyplay/build/marketing` instead of `/opt/readyplay/marketing`). The process crashlooped 15,542 times before the operator noticed. Every prior deploy's `pm2 restart` reused the bad config, so the bug was self-renewing across every deploy. The recovery was `pm2 delete && pm2 start --cwd /opt/readyplay/marketing --interpreter /usr/bin/node` + `pm2 save`.

## The rule

Every recoverable disaster in the ReadyPlay ecosystem (marketing, player-web, admin, api) MUST exist as a **cassette** in the Nephew Control Tower: one button → one whitelisted operator script → recovery executed on the VPS via the existing SSE-stream bridge.

Every cassette MUST also have a **heredoc-safe paste-block** in `READYPLAY_PASTE_BLOCK` (in `apps/control-tower/src/lib/readyplay-operator.ts`) so the operator can recover by direct shell when the Tower itself is the thing that's down.

## The cassette stack (every recovery flows through these four layers)

| Layer | File | Purpose |
|---|---|---|
| 1. Shell dispatcher | `nephew/scripts/readyplay-recovery.sh` | One file. One subcommand per recovery. Idempotent. Auto-detects local-on-VPS vs SSH-from-Mac. |
| 2. Make targets | `nephew/Makefile` (`readyplay-*` targets) | Wraps each subcommand for direct CLI use AND for the operator-script bridge. |
| 3. Whitelisted operator script | `nephew/data/operator-scripts.manifest.json` (`readyplay` section) | Server-operator only honors IDs in this manifest. Frontend never passes raw commands. |
| 4. Native CT card | `nephew/apps/control-tower/src/pages/ReadyPlayRecoveryPage.tsx` + `lib/readyplay-operator.ts` + manifest row in `data/native-cards.manifest.json` | Renders the cassette grid + output console + paste-block clipboard. Auto-routed via `import.meta.glob` per cassette-discipline. |

## Adding a new recovery cassette

When a new ReadyPlay disaster recovery is identified:

1. **Shell** — add a `cmd_<name>()` function in `scripts/readyplay-recovery.sh` + a case branch in `main()`. Subcommand name = kebab-case ("admin-pm2-fix").
2. **Make** — add `readyplay-<name>:` target. Update `.PHONY` line.
3. **Operator-script manifest** — add a row to the `readyplay` section.
4. **Frontend lib** — add to `READYPLAY_SCRIPT` (the constants object), `READYPLAY_PASTE_BLOCK` (the heredoc string for direct-shell use), and `READYPLAY_CASSETTES` (the metadata array the page iterates).
5. **CHANGELOG + version bump** per [`version-bump-and-changelog`](version-bump-and-changelog.md).
6. **No other edits.** No `App.tsx` edit, no router change, no nav file change. The cassette pattern handles routing through manifest iteration.

## When the rule fires

- A ReadyPlay outage is recovered manually — the recovery procedure MUST land as a cassette before the session closes
- A new known-failure mode is identified — add an audit cassette (read-only) before adding a fix cassette
- A Pain Journal entry is added to `red-e-play-app/CLAUDE.md` describing a recoverable pattern — file a cassette to match

## When the rule does NOT fire

- One-off SSH commands the operator runs interactively (cleanup, debugging) — only persistent procedures become cassettes
- Recovery procedures that require human judgment (deciding between rollback strategies, picking a SHA) — those stay as runbooks, not buttons
- Backend (`readyplay-api`) data-layer recovery (migrations, dump/restore) — different blast radius, separate plan

## What goes wrong without this rule

- Operator memorizes the pm2-cwd-recovery one-liner, then forgets it two months later when the bug recurs
- Recovery procedures live only in chat transcripts, become unfindable
- Every new agent landing in the session has to re-derive the fix
- Tower has no operator-actionable surface for production recovery — every disaster forces a SSH-from-Mac session even when the operator is sitting in front of the Tower

## What good looks like

- Every ReadyPlay outage that's happened more than once has a button
- Each button has a paste-block fallback for when the Tower is the broken thing
- The plan doc (`plans/0069-readyplay-recovery-cassette.md`) is the durable record of why each cassette exists
- The Pain Journal entry in `red-e-play-app/CLAUDE.md` points at the cassette by name so the next debug session finds it immediately

## Origin incident — 2026-05-23

- `pm2 jlist | jq` showed `readyplay-marketing` had `pm_cwd = "/opt/readyplay/build/marketing"` (wrong) instead of `"/opt/readyplay/marketing"` (correct)
- `exec_interpreter = "/home/abrownsanta/.cursor-server/bin/linux-x64/<sha>/node"` (fragile — breaks when Cursor's remote SSH session updates)
- `restart_time = 15542` (crashlooping for hours/days)
- `next start` error: `Could not find a production build in the '.next' directory` (because cwd had no `.next/`)
- Fix: `pm2 delete readyplay-marketing && cd /opt/readyplay/marketing && pm2 start node_modules/next/dist/bin/next --cwd /opt/readyplay/marketing --interpreter /usr/bin/node -- start --port 3003 && pm2 save`
- HTTP 200 restored within seconds.

